titleStmt.title: Letter from Eoghan mac Phaill to Eóin Ó Conchubhair

note.p: Emendations attributed NLS Adv. MS 72.3.11 are by from a transcription of this text made by (1743-1808) in that MS on pp.1-27. This transcription shows that damage to NLS Adv. MS 72.1.34 occurred subsequent to his transcription.

In Donald Mackintosh's (1743–1808) transcription of this text, writing appears after the word Lochlannach. It reaches the edge of the page which is somewhat damaged at this time, thus making it difficult to be certain of the end of the word. The present transcriber/editor thinks that the text reads "an feachdnais". Ó Cróinín 1995 supplies "dar ba comhainm" here.
Ó Cróinín 1995 supplies "Dathchaoin Tréin" here.

Although these MS pages were intact when Donald Macintosh had access to this text, his transcription is not always completely reliable. At times he mistakes letter forms, e.g. he takes the f in faithe (p.1, l.5) as an s. An example of where he is unsure what the text he is transcribing means occurs at p2, l.1 where the MS clearly reads 'chath do thuath de danann' but Macintosh has written 'is do chaidhe d. d.' (NLS Adv 72.3.11, p.1, l.16). Later in this text it becomes clear that Mac Pháill's t is often close to a d but upon closer examination they are in fact ts. Such an example can be found on p.2, l.5 where Macintosh writes 'do duit' for the MS's 'do tuit'. For this reason, the present editor postulates that the Mac Pháill wrote tuireadh rather than duiread in the original. Furthermore, Macintosh, who was using modern word spacing writes duireadna as a single entity, suggesting that he did not know it was two words and thus that he did not know what tuireadh was in this context.
As with the instance of tuireadh in l.2 it is likely that Mac Pháill wrote this word with an initial t.

Here Donald Macintosh has something which appears to be a lowercase a with a somewhat rounded i ascending from the top left of the letter. Macintosh does not seem to have always understood the text and the present editor postulates that Ó Cróinín's interpretation of this, i.e. that don was originally written in the MS is correct as do is the preposition most freuqently used with taobh elsewhere in this MS, e.g. p.2, l.4; p.5, ll.4, 5; p.17, ll.6, 9.

Ó Cróinín prints 'Clár Luighue' in his semi-diplomatic (p. 221, l.19) and diplomatic (p. 163, l.18) editions. In his notes (p. 180) he says 'Tá an litriú truaillithe anseo agus níor éirigh liom an logainm seo a aimsiú.' To the present editor, however, the form of the letter after the g appears to be clearly an n.

Regarding cruinnidur, (l.16), and dhainghnidur, here, Ó Cróinín says "Is ait liom na foirmeacha seo. Is briathra den dara réimniú iad seo agus ar an gcéad éachtaint is cosúil gur cuireadh sa chéad réimniú anseo iad. B'fhéidir gur sampla de hapology atá againn anseo .i. scríobhadh litir nó siolla amháin san áit a bhfuil dhá cheann ó cheart. Dá mba rud é go raibh chruinnidhidar agus do dhaingniudhadur os comhair an scríobhaí d'fhéadfadh sé dearmad a dhéanamh go fuirist agus gan ach id amháin a thabhairt leis ina thrascríbhinn. Is míniú sásúil é seo, dar liom, go háirithe nuair a chuirtear san áireamh go bhfuil dh agus gh meascaithe le chéile tríd síos sa lámhscríbhinn."

Ó Cróinín (pp.181-2) says '[..] tá seans go mbaineann sé seo le canúint an údair. B'fhéidir go léiríonn an litriú anseo canúint thusisceartach nó Albannach ach ba dheacair aon ahdmad ar leith a bhaint as an sampla seo toisc nach bhfuil a thuilleadh samplaí sa téacs. Is deimhneach nach foirm liteartha í seo, áfach, agus is é is dealraithí ná gur éalaigh an fhoirm ó pheann an údair i ngan fhios dó.'

Ó Cróinín emends this to do bhéar (p.164) and notes (p.182) '[...] leasaíodh é seo ós rud é gur cosúil go bhfuil raibh [sic] mearbhall ar an scríobhaí idir an chéad agus an dara pearsa uatha anseo. Míodhach atá ga [sic] caint le Fionn anseo.' Ó Cróinín's aim was to produce a text that was 'soléite do léitheoir a bhfuil taithí aige ar an Nua-Ghaeilge' (p. 36). The different emmendation here is due to the present editor remaining as close to the original as possible, only emmending what is necessary for the text to make sense.
The -a in triucha here is supplied silently in Ó Cróinín's edited text (p.165).)

Ó Cróinín prints tren in the edited text (p. 169) and in the diplomatic edition (p. 227). While the present editor agrees with this interpretaition interpretaion they cannot see any trace of an n, nor indication in the manuscript of one having faded, been rubbed out or deleted.
Instead of ttionol Donald Macintosh has 'da ttaitnadh an teannadh'.
In the MS sealga was written before suibhne but marks in the MS indicate that they should have been written in reverse order.

The MS is damaged here. As the end of the descender of the f and its cross stroke are still visible, and as the meaning is clear, it has been transcribed as an f. The damage extends to the second letter of the word which may have been an i or e. Due to the regularity with which Mac Pháill writes i in this name in this text it has here been taken as an i.
The word ceann does not appear in the MS yet Ó Cróinín supplies it without any indication that he has done so in his edited (p. 171) and diplomatic (p.229) texts.
Ó Cróinín gives this as "rí eile" in edited text (p.171) but Lochlann in "diplomatic" (p.230).
There is an opening bracket here but it is never closed in this text so it does not seem to have any meaning. Due to being incongruous it had been emeded out of the text in the present edition.
In the MS "da dorn is written before "cuid" but marks in the MS denote that the two should swap places.
Donald_Macintosh_(1743-1808) writes 'da cois amhulad anochda'.
Ó Cróinín silently supplies the fh here, both in the "diplomatic" and edited texts.

The scribe may have intended to write eolachtach, or something akin to it, or may have accidentally indicated the end of the word with both a suspension stroke-lenition dot combination and then written out plene. As the present editor has no other examples of eolachtach the reading has been emended to eolach.

The name of this féinnid is usually rendered as "Dubh Dá Bhoireann" but "bf" when we would expect a lenited "b" is something that occurs elsewhere in this MS, i.e. "a bfias" (p8.22) and "nior obfhrus) (p16.11), both of which occur in the same text. Thus, although uncommon, it is nonetheless a feature of this text.

The suspension stroke above in the word eirigh extends to the right and curves down towards the ar-abbreviation. This appears to be for the letter i. This could eithe be classified as a form of the air-abbreviation, or as a superscript i and the ar-abbreviation. The present editor has taken it as the latter.

Before both righ and feinnidh here the letters a that have been emended out of the edition are in superscript. In other cases where we find use of superscript a, we find a corresponding b to indicate that the reader should change the order from that written on the page. In this case, however, reading feinnidh before righ would not make sense. Perhaps mac Pháill thought a correction was to be made and noted a superscript a before righ but subsequently saw that he had written the text correctly and opted to confirm this by also writing a superscript a before feinnidh, or perhaps these have another purpose unknown to the present editor.

Ní Shéaghdha takes dtugus as a single word, a form of do-beir and supplies an i before the final s. The present editor is of the opinion that no emendation of hte text is necessary if us is understood to be the emphatic form of tú.
There is a punctum above this Tironian Nota but the present editor cannot account for how it could be added to the text at this point.
fiochmura is written before fiana in the manuscript but the scribe has inserted a number of addition marks which indicate that the two words be read in reverse order.
It is also possible that the "crunn" here is the adjective cruinn.
Black (0002498)says that "The form geubhadh seems to be required both metrically [and] morphologically. Probably a suspension stroke has simply been omitted."
Black (0110468) says that the form obar is required for rhyme with cogar."
Black supplies this in the HDSG slip for this line (0030416).
If not furthain, maybe a form of airrinde, http://dil.ie/2371? Black (0131226) did not know the meaning of this word.
